1. Bronze Layer: Data Ingestion & Staging
The Bronze layer is the "Raw" landing zone. Here, data is moved from external CSV files into MySQL Staging Tables.

Why Use Staging Tables?
Persistence: External CSV files can be moved, deleted, or altered. Staging tables provide a stable, immutable record of the raw data within the database.

Auditability: By keeping raw data in staging tables, we can always trace a "Gold" insight back to its "Bronze" source to verify accuracy.

Performance: SQL-based joins and transformations in the Silver layer are more efficient when performed on database tables rather than re-reading multiple flat files from a disk.

Ingestion Logic (Python)
Modular Processing: A configuration dictionary allows the pipeline to loop through files from different networks (VMobile, Blue, Arrow) using a single, modular code block.

clean_headers Function: Cleans raw CSV headers using string manipulation to ensure they are SQL-compliant (removing spaces and special characters).

read_file_safe Function: A robust utility that detects delimiters (commas vs. semicolons) and uses "coerce" errors to handle malformed numeric data without breaking the pipeline.

2. Silver Layer: Standardization & Master Data Management (MDM)
The Silver layer is the "Source of Truth." This is where data is cleansed, standardized, and deduplicated to identify the Master Record.

Data Cleansing & Python Regex
Phone Number Standardization: Used Regular Expressions (Regex) to strip non-digit characters and string slicing to ensure all South African MSISDNs follow a consistent 10-digit format (e.g., prepending "0").

Date Parsing: Converted raw strings into Python date objects. This enabled mathematical operations to determine reporting windows (Monday start to Sunday end).

MDM & SQL Logic
To identify the "Master Record" among duplicates across three networks, the following logic was applied:

Sorting & Ranking: Used Python to sort the unified DataFrame by Source Priority (VMobile > Blue > Arrow) and SIM Activation Date (most recent first).

Deduplication: Iterated through sorted data to flag the first occurrence of a unique cellphone number as isMasterRecord = True.

Duplicates Table: An all-encompassing table used for auditing every record received.

No-Duplicates Table: A high-fidelity table containing only unique Master Records, serving as the primary Dimension Table for the warehouse.

3. Gold Layer: Aggregation & Business Insights
The Gold layer implements a Star Schema designed for executive reporting and campaign evaluation.

It consists of physcial tables aswell, and not VIEWS. This is because physcial tables provide faster read times. However upon completion of the project, I realized that I should have gone with views since the use case was more ad-hoc related. Spped was not of the essence(only required at the end of every week. Views also have lower costs than physical table storage.

Feature Engineering & SQL Aggregation
Usage Aggregation: Utilized SQL Group By and Aggregate Functions (SUM, COUNT) to transform row-level usage events into weekly subscriber summaries.

Qualification Filter: Implemented logic to identify "Qualifying Subscribers" who generated a revenue of R30 or more within a specific reporting week.

Data Enrichment: Performed Inner Joins between the Usage data and the "No-Duplicates" Master table to bring in geographic regions and subscriber names.

The Star Schema
Fact Table: Qualifying_Subscriber_table (contains weekly revenue, call counts, and SMS volume).

Dimension Tables: Combined_table_no_duplicates (contains unique subscriber metadata and regions).

4. Automated Reporting
The pipeline concludes with an automated reporting engine using Python's XlsxWriter.

Dynamic Pivot Tables: The data is structured to support Excel Pivot Tables, allowing the Marketing team to slice revenue by "Reporting Date" and "Region."

User-Centric Design: Final headers are converted to uppercase and standardized for a clean, professional executive summary.

Personal Lessons & Technical Insights
Database Constraints & Idempotency
Foreign Key Challenges: I encountered an error when trying to TRUNCATE the Master table because it was referenced by a Foreign Key in the Qualifying table.

The Solution: I implemented a "Drop and Recreate" strategy. This taught me the importance of Idempotency—ensuring that my ETL pipeline can be run repeatedly from scratch without failing due to existing data or constraints.

Python-to-SQL Limitations
.to_sql() Type Mapping: I learned that Pandas doesn't always automatically detect SQL types correctly. I had to explicitly define a dtype dictionary (specifying Date and Decimal types) to ensure the data was inserted into MySQL correctly.

Join Redundancy: When merging DataFrames in Python, I realized that Joins often create duplicate columns (like cellphone_number_x and _y). I had to implement a final column-selection step to ensure the DataFrame matched the MySQL table schema exactly before insertion.

Architectural Reflections
Separation of Concerns: I realized I should have separated "Phone Cleaning" from "Date Cleaning." Combining them into one function made it difficult to reuse the phone-cleaning logic later in the pipeline without also triggering date processing.

Schema Normalization: I noticed I calculated week dates twice (for the DB and the report). While storing these in the database would reduce CPU cycles, it would have required a more complex normalized schema to maintain 3rd Normal Form.
